00:32.128 --> 00:35.032
LEONARDO DICAPRIO: My first
visual memories are of this

00:35.065 --> 00:38.469
framed poster above my crib.

00:43.341 --> 00:46.244
I would stare at it every
night before I went to bed.

00:51.048 --> 00:54.285
My father was an underground
comic distributor.

00:54.319 --> 00:57.255
He's always been this sort of
Zelig of the counterculture

00:57.288 --> 00:59.224
as I like to call him.

00:59.257 --> 01:02.793
Having painted in
Warhol's studio,

01:02.827 --> 01:06.897
being roomies with Lou
Reed, he knew R. Crumb

01:06.931 --> 01:10.100
and all these great
artists of his generation.

01:10.134 --> 01:14.138
I mean, I was brought up on all
kinds of wacky visuals as a kid.

01:15.573 --> 01:20.778
So I would stare at this
painting over and over:

01:20.811 --> 01:24.982
The Garden of Earthly Delights
by Hieronymus Bosch.

01:29.019 --> 01:32.056
It was painted around 1500.

01:32.089 --> 01:34.825
And if you look at these
panels long enough,

01:34.859 --> 01:36.527
they start to tell a story.

01:39.364 --> 01:43.534
In the first panel you have Adam
and Eve in the Garden of Eden.

01:43.568 --> 01:46.103
Birds flying off
into the distance,

01:46.136 --> 01:50.975
elephants and giraffe and a
lot of religious iconography.

01:51.008 --> 01:53.444
The second panel is where
it starts to become

01:53.478 --> 01:56.247
more interesting.

01:56.281 --> 01:59.384
The deadly sins start to infuse
their way into the painting.

01:59.417 --> 02:03.188
There's overpopulation,
there's debauchery and excess.

02:06.257 --> 02:10.360
And the last panel, which
is the most nightmarish one,

02:10.395 --> 02:16.601
especially from a young child's
perspective, is this twisted,

02:16.634 --> 02:20.238
decayed, burnt landscape.

02:21.372 --> 02:25.576
A paradise that has been
degraded and destroyed.

02:25.610 --> 02:31.482
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

02:31.516 --> 02:33.951
NEWS MEDIA: Man may be
unwittingly changing the world's

02:33.984 --> 02:37.355
climate through the waste
products of its civilization...

02:37.388 --> 02:41.025
The burning of coal, oil and
wood is releasing carbon dioxide

02:41.058 --> 02:43.127
into the atmosphere.

02:43.160 --> 02:46.497
The greenhouse effect has been
detected and it is changing

02:46.531 --> 02:48.299
our climate now.

02:48.333 --> 02:51.001
Guess where the
temperature goes?

02:51.035 --> 02:53.471
It goes up.

02:53.504 --> 02:55.540
Climate change is
already in our backyards.

02:55.573 --> 02:57.542
It's official. 2012 was the
hottest year in the...

02:57.575 --> 02:58.643
... 2013

02:58.676 --> 03:00.110
... 2014

03:00.144 --> 03:01.212
... 2015

03:01.246 --> 03:02.480
... warmest year around the globe

03:02.513 --> 03:03.914
... warmest year on record.

03:03.948 --> 03:07.017
It is these activities
that drove mankind

03:07.051 --> 03:08.286
out of the Garden of Eden.

03:17.061 --> 03:18.596
DICAPRIO: Hi, how are you?
KI‐MOON: Ah, Mr. DiCaprio.

03:18.629 --> 03:19.564
DICAPRIO: Pleasure, pleasure.

03:19.597 --> 03:22.433
KI‐MOON: Great to, great
pleasure to see you.

03:22.467 --> 03:24.335
Here.

03:24.369 --> 03:26.136
We can move this.

03:26.171 --> 03:28.105
This can be adjusted.

03:28.138 --> 03:29.174
DICAPRIO: Oh wow, this
is for height control.

03:29.207 --> 03:30.575
KI‐MOON: Yeah.

03:30.608 --> 03:32.277
Like this, like this.
DICAPRIO: For shorter leaders

03:32.310 --> 03:34.612
and taller leaders.

03:34.645 --> 03:37.648
What specific message do you
think is the most important?

03:37.682 --> 03:41.252
KI‐MOON: Climate change is
coming much, much faster.

03:41.286 --> 03:46.090
We have seen such, uh,
extraordinary extreme weather

03:46.123 --> 03:47.992
patterns.

03:48.025 --> 03:51.429
If you consider this
vastness of this universe,

03:51.462 --> 03:55.099
this Planet Earth is
just a small boat.

03:55.132 --> 03:59.604
If this boat is sinking, then
I think we will have to all

03:59.637 --> 04:01.206
sink together.

04:03.007 --> 04:06.677
I know that he has been a
very committed and effective

04:06.711 --> 04:11.616
environmentalist and that is
why I really count on your

04:11.649 --> 04:13.684
leadership and vision.

04:15.453 --> 04:18.189
ANNOUNCER: Please welcome
newly appointed United Nations

04:18.223 --> 04:22.427
Messenger of Peace,
Mr. Leonardo DiCaprio.

04:22.460 --> 04:27.432
[APPLAUSE]

04:27.465 --> 04:29.600
DICAPRIO: Thank you
Mr. Secretary General,

04:29.634 --> 04:31.101
Your Excellencies...

04:31.135 --> 04:33.338
I feel incredibly honored
that they chose me to be

04:33.371 --> 04:36.341
the United Nations Messenger
of Peace on climate change.

04:36.374 --> 04:39.610
I stand before
you, not as an expert,

04:39.644 --> 04:44.014
I want to do everything I can
to learn more about this issue.

04:44.048 --> 04:49.019
See for myself exactly what's
going on and what can be done.

04:49.053 --> 04:52.457
But it all kinda seems
beyond our control.

04:52.490 --> 04:55.626
As an actor,
I pretend for a living.

04:55.660 --> 04:58.729
I play fictitious characters
often solving fictitious

04:58.763 --> 05:00.531
problems.

05:00.565 --> 05:03.401
I believe that mankind has
looked at climate change

05:03.434 --> 05:05.135
in that same way.

05:05.170 --> 05:07.438
We keep getting inundated with
catastrophic news about the

05:07.472 --> 05:11.075
environment every single day,
and the problem seems to be

05:11.108 --> 05:15.180
getting worse and
worse and worse.

05:15.213 --> 05:18.148
Try to have a conversation with
anyone about climate change,

05:18.183 --> 05:19.550
people just tune out.

05:19.584 --> 05:22.353
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

05:22.387 --> 05:26.191
If the U. N. really knew
how I feel,

05:26.224 --> 05:33.030
how pessimistic I am about our
future, I mean, to be honest,

05:33.063 --> 05:35.333
they may have picked
the wrong guy.

05:37.802 --> 05:39.069
NEWSCASTER: Hundreds of
thousands took to the streets

05:39.103 --> 05:44.309
of New York today demonstrating
for action on climate change.

05:44.342 --> 05:47.044
NEWSCASTER: Secretary General,
Ban Ki‐Moon called Leo

05:47.077 --> 05:49.580
a credible voice in the
environmental movement,

05:49.614 --> 05:52.350
which is like calling Jeffrey
Dahmer a credible voice

05:52.383 --> 05:54.118
for stew.

05:54.151 --> 05:57.355
NEWSCASTER: Leonardo DiCaprio
has just naively bought into

05:57.388 --> 05:59.657
the entire global warming hoax.

05:59.690 --> 06:01.759
NEWSCASTER: Who better to
educate world leaders on made up

06:01.792 --> 06:05.363
climate change in a crisis that
doesn't exist than an actor

06:05.396 --> 06:08.199
from Hollywood with zero years
of scientific training?

06:08.233 --> 06:17.408
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

06:18.776 --> 06:19.610
DICAPRIO: Hi, how are you?

06:19.644 --> 06:20.845
WOMAN: I'm very good.

06:20.878 --> 06:22.247
DICAPRIO: How are you doing,
it's a pleasure.

06:22.280 --> 06:23.113
WOMAN: You too.

06:26.484 --> 06:26.951
ALEJANDRO: Hey!

06:26.984 --> 06:28.052
[BACKGROUND VOICE]

06:31.756 --> 06:33.224
DICAPRIO: Nice to
see you, buddy.

06:33.258 --> 06:34.492
ALFONSO CUARON: Good to see you.

06:34.525 --> 06:38.529
So I just started this new film,
it's set in the Western Frontier

06:38.563 --> 06:41.832
of the United States
in the early 1800s.

06:41.866 --> 06:44.735
It's basically the dawn of
the Industrial Revolution.

06:44.769 --> 06:48.273
It has a lot to do with men who
are pillaging the natural world,

06:48.306 --> 06:51.242
wiping species out, and
basically destroying cultures

06:51.276 --> 06:52.377
in the process.

06:52.410 --> 06:54.845
Those are like buffalo skulls.

06:54.879 --> 06:56.281
Alejandro!

06:56.314 --> 06:59.484
Crazy, are these fur‐trappers?

06:59.517 --> 07:01.118
Are these people
selling the skulls?

07:01.151 --> 07:03.521
ALEJANDRO: No, these are people
selling the skulls, yeah.

07:03.554 --> 07:05.356
DICAPRIO: What the
[BLEEP] is this?

07:05.390 --> 07:06.591
ALEJANDRO: Isn't
that embarrassing?

07:06.624 --> 07:08.293
DICAPRIO: Man, that's crazy.

07:08.326 --> 07:09.827
ALEJANDRO: And the fact that
they never even reflected on it,

07:09.860 --> 07:12.663
that there's an ending to these
animals, and we cannot just,

07:12.697 --> 07:13.864
it's insane.

07:13.898 --> 07:15.533
DICAPRIO: If you can put that
in the movie that would be

07:15.566 --> 07:17.735
unbelievable.

07:17.768 --> 07:18.803
How about this, I dare you!

07:18.836 --> 07:21.439
ALEJANDRO: Ah, okay.

07:21.472 --> 07:25.610
... get to the boat. Come on son.
[GUNSHOTS]

07:28.813 --> 07:30.848
I didn't grow up
around nature at all,

07:30.881 --> 07:35.453
I grew up near
downtown Los Angeles.

07:35.486 --> 07:40.558
And my escape every weekend was
the Natural History Museum.

07:40.591 --> 07:44.462
And from a very young age, I
became fascinated with species

07:44.495 --> 07:47.198
that had become extinct.

07:47.232 --> 07:48.599
All these different animals,

07:48.633 --> 07:50.935
from the dodo to the
passenger pigeon,

07:50.968 --> 07:53.571
which was the most
plentiful bird on earth,

07:53.604 --> 07:57.208
to the Tasmanian tiger, also
known as the thilacene

07:57.242 --> 08:00.578
to the great auk, the
quagga, the moa.

08:00.611 --> 08:03.514
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

08:03.548 --> 08:05.583
I remember the
anger that I felt,

08:05.616 --> 08:08.886
reading all these stories about
how explorers and settlers

08:08.919 --> 08:13.791
would just wipe out an entire
species, and in the process,

08:13.824 --> 08:16.427
decimate the ecosystem forever.

08:16.461 --> 08:25.936
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

08:25.970 --> 08:30.408
The difference now is we're
knowingly doing this;

08:32.777 --> 08:35.380
it's just on a
much larger scale.

08:43.621 --> 08:46.291
BRUNE: If we're gonna fight
climate change effectively,

08:46.324 --> 08:48.293
we have to start by
acknowledging that

08:48.326 --> 08:51.562
most of our economy is
based on fossil fuels.

08:51.596 --> 08:56.434
Fossil fuels are coal,
oil, and natural gas.

08:56.467 --> 08:58.569
Oil powers most of the
transportation sector,

09:02.373 --> 09:06.211
coal and natural gas power
most of the electricity.

09:08.279 --> 09:11.682
Now, in the first couple decades
of the twenty‐first century,

09:11.716 --> 09:15.386
in order to sustain our
dependence on fossil fuels,

09:15.420 --> 09:19.390
we're going to very risky,
very extreme new sources.

09:19.424 --> 09:22.527
[EXPLOSIONS]

09:22.560 --> 09:25.930
You see this in things like
mountain top removal for coal,

09:28.833 --> 09:30.501
fracking for natural gas,

09:34.572 --> 09:36.674
offshore drilling for oil,

09:39.610 --> 09:43.448
and the tar sands, which is
the most devastating form

09:43.481 --> 09:46.517
of producing fossil fuels.

09:46.551 --> 09:50.688
They take away massive forests,
the water in the streams

09:50.721 --> 09:52.957
and rivers is poisoned.

09:52.990 --> 09:57.295
It has severe impacts on the
wildlife, on native communities,

09:57.328 --> 10:02.800
and it requires a huge amount of
energy simply to get it to

10:02.833 --> 10:03.768
our fuel tanks.

10:05.770 --> 10:08.072
There is no such thing
as clean fossil fuel.

10:08.105 --> 10:09.707
PILOT: Headsets are
hung up at the back,

10:09.740 --> 10:11.376
but the volume control's right
above the microphone so...

11:50.941 --> 11:54.078
DICAPRIO: The truth is, the more
I've learned about this issue

11:54.111 --> 11:57.848
and everything that
contributes to the problem,

11:57.882 --> 12:00.418
the more I realize
how much I don't know.

12:01.219 --> 12:03.120
How much I don't know
about this issue.

12:05.656 --> 12:08.793
The first time I ever heard
the term global warming,

12:08.826 --> 12:10.628
which was what it
was called back then,

12:10.661 --> 12:12.730
I was in my early twenties.

12:12.763 --> 12:15.533
I had the opportunity to sit
down one on one with then

12:15.566 --> 12:18.969
Vice President, Al Gore
in the White House.

12:19.003 --> 12:22.072
And he drew a picture of
our planet on a chalkboard,

12:22.106 --> 12:24.642
and then he drew the atmosphere
around it, and he said,

12:24.675 --> 12:28.213
this is the most important
issue of our time.

12:28.246 --> 12:32.483
I had absolutely no idea
what he was talking about.

12:32.517 --> 12:35.720
He said all our modes of
transportation, boats, trains,

12:35.753 --> 12:38.456
planes, cars, the way
we produce our food,

12:38.489 --> 12:41.025
the way we build our cities,
almost everything we do releases

12:41.058 --> 12:47.232
carbon dioxide, CO2, and that
leads to climate change.

12:47.265 --> 12:49.099
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

12:49.133 --> 12:52.203
The polar ice caps will melt,
the seas will start to rise,

12:52.237 --> 12:55.139
there will be more dangerous
weather patterns, floods,

12:55.173 --> 12:57.107
droughts, wildfires.

12:57.141 --> 13:00.010
It sounded like some nightmarish
science fiction film.

13:00.044 --> 13:02.480
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

13:02.513 --> 13:04.615
Except everything
he said is real

13:04.649 --> 13:06.116
and it's happening right now.

13:06.150 --> 13:13.558
♪ [MUSIC] ♪

13:13.591 --> 13:14.992
DICAPRIO: Wow.

13:15.025 --> 13:15.860
Wow.

13:15.893 --> 13:16.861
Beautiful.

13:22.132 --> 13:25.736
I just want to know
how far we've gone,

13:25.770 --> 13:29.607
how much damage we've done, and
if there's anything we can do

13:29.640 --> 13:31.609
to stop it.

13:36.847 --> 13:37.289
MAN: You all set, mate?

13:41.952 --> 13:43.788
DICAPRIO: So it's
the 4th of July,

13:43.821 --> 13:46.023
and we're here in the
middle of the Arctic.

13:46.056 --> 13:48.793
DR. SALA: Right now we are
standing on the ocean,

13:48.826 --> 13:51.128
we are basically
walking on water.

13:51.161 --> 13:53.798
This is the northern
tip of Baffin Island,

13:53.831 --> 13:56.967
one of the hundreds of islands
in the High Canadian Arctic.

13:57.001 --> 13:59.770
We are way above
the Arctic Circle,

13:59.804 --> 14:01.806
and if you put your
hand in the water,

14:01.839 --> 14:04.542
you would not be able to stand
it for more than 5 minutes,

14:07.011 --> 14:09.046
except you who are a badass.

14:09.079 --> 14:10.215
DICAPRIO: You hunt
and fish here, right?

14:10.248 --> 14:12.016
AWA: Yeah.

14:12.049 --> 14:13.751
DICAPRIO: What do you, what do
you fish and what do you hunt?

14:13.784 --> 14:18.623
AWA: In my territory I
hunt fish, seal, narwhal,

14:18.656 --> 14:19.990
and polar bear.

14:20.024 --> 14:21.158
DICAPRIO: Is this polar bear?
AWA: Yup.

14:21.192 --> 14:23.261
DICAPRIO: Oh, well there you go!

14:23.294 --> 14:26.797
And the ice here, since you've
been around has it been

14:26.831 --> 14:27.698
decreasing?

14:27.732 --> 14:31.001
AWA: We used to have
a solid ice, blue.

14:31.035 --> 14:33.037
Not light blue like this, blue.

14:33.070 --> 14:34.805
Hard, ice.

14:34.839 --> 14:42.713
Now we usually have a, kind
of ice cream type of ice.

14:42.747 --> 14:44.982
It's ice but it's,
when it starts to melt,

14:45.015 --> 14:46.884
it melts pretty fast.

14:46.917 --> 14:49.119
Much faster than before.

14:49.153 --> 14:54.925
DR. SALA: 2040, you will be able
to sail over the North Pole.

14:54.959 --> 14:57.995
There's going to be no sea
ice left in the Arctic Ocean

14:58.028 --> 14:59.797
in the summer.

14:59.830 --> 15:03.168
We are burning so many fossil
fuels that the ice is melting.

15:06.237 --> 15:09.274
The Arctic is like
the air conditioning for

15:09.307 --> 15:11.376
the Northern Hemisphere.

15:11.409 --> 15:14.679
If it goes away, that's
going to change currents,

15:14.712 --> 15:17.047
that's going to change
weather patterns,

15:17.081 --> 15:21.852
that's going to make floods and
droughts more catastrophic.

15:21.886 --> 15:25.723
It's the most dramatic
transformation of a large

15:25.756 --> 15:26.991
environment ever.

15:30.995 --> 15:31.596
Look at this.

15:34.399 --> 15:37.368
DICAPRIO: They're right here!

15:37.402 --> 15:40.671
DR. SALA: There are about 10,000
to 12,000 narwhals

15:40.705 --> 15:42.807
in this region.

15:42.840 --> 15:46.377
The numbers are stable here,
in other regions are declining.

15:46.411 --> 15:48.713
DICAPRIO: Wow.

15:48.746 --> 15:50.648
That's awesome.

15:50.681 --> 15:53.984
DR. SALA: Yeah, they are
waiting for the ice to open up,

15:54.018 --> 15:57.021
to swim in, so they
can catch the flounder.

15:57.054 --> 16:02.159
DICAPRIO: I can't believe what
they sound like, it's amazing.

16:02.193 --> 16:03.027
They're like purring.

16:06.764 --> 16:08.199
DR. SALA: You know, I don't
want to be in a planet

16:08.233 --> 16:09.700
without these animals.

16:17.842 --> 16:19.377
ANNOUNCER: He's the
chairman of Earth Day 2000,

16:19.410 --> 16:20.878
Leonardo DiCaprio.

16:20.911 --> 16:23.080
DICAPRIO: When I
was 25 years old,

16:23.113 --> 16:26.184
I remember being asked to
participate in this huge event

16:26.217 --> 16:27.985
in Washington for Earth Day.

16:28.018 --> 16:30.955
Temperatures are rising,
coral reefs are dying,

16:30.988 --> 16:34.392
and not since a meteor hit the
earth 65 million years ago,

16:34.425 --> 16:37.061
have so many species of plant
and animals become extinct

16:37.094 --> 16:38.329
in such a short time.

16:38.363 --> 16:40.198
I even got a chance to
interview the President

16:40.231 --> 16:41.866
of the United States.

16:41.899 --> 16:44.369
Why do you think this issue
is so constantly overlooked?

16:44.402 --> 16:46.971
BILL CLINTON: I think it's
because it takes a long time

16:47.004 --> 16:49.474
for the climate to change in
a way that people feel it,

16:49.507 --> 16:53.878
and because, uh, it seems
sort of abstract now.

16:53.911 --> 16:56.247
DICAPRIO: At the time, it was
this huge push to get the word

16:56.281 --> 16:57.948
out on global warming.

16:57.982 --> 17:00.117
Now a couple degrees' difference
in today's temperatures

17:00.150 --> 17:02.820
may not seem like an emergency.

17:02.853 --> 17:07.090
Back then everyone was focused
on small, individual actions.

17:07.124 --> 17:10.194
We all have to, you know, bring
environmentalism to the American

17:10.228 --> 17:11.796
consciousness.

17:11.829 --> 17:13.998
And it boiled down to simple
solutions like changing

17:14.031 --> 17:16.934
your light bulb.

17:16.967 --> 17:20.104
It seemed like a positive
thing at the time, you know.

17:20.137 --> 17:21.839
Changing your lightbulb.

17:24.008 --> 17:27.212
But it's pretty clear that we're
way beyond that point now;

17:27.244 --> 17:30.014
things have taken a
massive turn for the worst.

17:33.451 --> 17:36.086
BOX: We keep finding things that
aren't in the climate models

17:36.120 --> 17:38.055
that are used to
project the future.

17:38.088 --> 17:42.026
So that, that tells me that the
projections for the future are,

17:42.059 --> 17:44.829
are really conservative.

17:44.862 --> 17:47.232
If climate stays at this
temperature that it's been

17:47.265 --> 17:50.835
in the last decade, Greenland
is, is going away.

17:53.804 --> 17:55.540
Don't walk into the crevasse.

17:55.573 --> 17:56.073
[Rapids].

17:56.106 --> 17:57.942
DICAPRIO: Oh my God!

17:57.975 --> 18:00.845
BOX: Don't get too
close to the edge.

18:00.878 --> 18:03.013
DICAPRIO: Look at
how violent that is.

18:03.047 --> 18:06.050
These rapids are going
so incredibly fast.

18:06.083 --> 18:08.319
BOX: This meltwater is
making its way to the sea.

18:08.353 --> 18:11.389
If that's not balanced by
snowfall then the ice sheet gets

18:11.422 --> 18:13.358
smaller and sea level rises.

18:16.827 --> 18:19.530
This is actually our
proper climate station.

18:19.564 --> 18:23.100
DICAPRIO: This is
a climate station?

18:23.133 --> 18:26.537
I was imagining a massive igloo
with all kinds of scientists

18:26.571 --> 18:28.138
doing experiments.

18:28.173 --> 18:33.278
